tal interaction more effective in the future. The book is organized into two parts. The first, more general, section compares the national contexts for environmental management in each country-including economic conditions, sociocultural dynamics, and political decision-making frameworks- and shows how these have led to variations in policy approaches and levels of capacity. The authors argue that effective environmental governance in North America depends on the ability of transboundary institutions to address and mediate these differences. The book's second section illustrates this argument, using four case studies of environmental management in North America: biodiversity and protected areas, air pollution (smog); greenhouse gas reduction, and genetically modified crops.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aEnvironmental managementzNorth AmericavCase studies. 0aEnvironmental managementzNorth America. 0aEnvironmental policyzNorth AmericavCase studies. 0aEnvironmental policyzNorth America. 4aCoursebook. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh1 aLópez-Vallejo, Marcela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aVanNijnatten, Debora L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269378440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442693784423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442693784.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK